{
  "text": " One pattern in tissue repair cases that plateau at about 80% and stop. Injury is old, sometimes years old, sometimes months. The protocol is well designed, right amino acids, right mineral cofactors, right movement rehab. Progress comes in the first phase, then it stalls. The body lands at maybe 75% of baseline function and refuses to close the gap. What I have come to watch for is the difference between inputs and signaling. You can add every nutrient on the list and still stall if the body is not receiving a repair signal. The cells need to know that the job is not finished. In cases like that, a signaling molecule often moves the needle when a tenth nutrient would not. Here's the one I reach for. In Finnewell, BPC157 rapid. The same pentadeca peptide in a faster release format targeted at soft tissue. Short course, tracked carefully, stopped when the plateau breaks, nutrients build, signaling decides the protocol stalls when the build is right and the signal is missing, not a forever protocol. A test input when the last 20% refuses to come back. Full pattern breakdown at tr.e slash owq7fm. Type it.",
